attributes.description:
Business Need: Needs Openshift for 50 Web Apps that are for internal use at FIS Global
Current Environment Size: 50 Web Apps
Existing Solution: Websphere
Timeframe: 3-6 months
Pain Points: End of life current solution Websphere
Why now? (Urgency): Has understanding from former employer Kohls and wants the eval for OSE for testing. 
Top 3 requirements: Slowly adopting DevOps, some of our technologies are reaching EOL, so we want to upgrade them. 
Decision Maker(s) Identified/Role of Contact (list out name and title/role): Pawan Rana Senior Development Manager
Budget: Yes
Partner or Direct: Direct
Next Steps: Potential Onsite Visit in Milwaukee from or onsite demo with Chris Norton and SA. 
Marketing Contribution Field Justification: Followed up on website visit and downloading collateral on Openshift. 
Notes/Write Up: 16 cores with App Services.

OpenShift
•	What is your company's plan for moving towards DevOps/becoming more Agile? 
o	Yes we are slowly adopting DevOps, some of our technologies are reaching EOL, so we want to upgrade them
•	How satisfied are you with current deployment times? 
o	Our current deploys are manual, want to automate as part of modernization 
•	How are you dealing with needs to be more agile and faster? 
o	Introducing Agile and DevOps
•	How long does it take for applications development and what is your process for application development? (remember OpenShift allows you CI/CD) 
o	No CI/CD implemented yet, planning to setup CI/CD
•	Would any of your current applications be better suited to be quickly spun up and consumed over a short period of time? If so, can you tell me a little more? 
o	At this point no? do you need this information for autoscaling? 
•	How often do you experience fluctuations in various parts of the year in terms of customers (internal or external) accessing applications? 
o	Not much with current application set I have, our peak season is from October to December
•	How many GBs of RAM does your applications use today (more for OpenShift Online) 
o	We will like to host internally in on our DCs
•	Are the applications you are planning to use with OpenShift Mission Critical? 
o	Not to start with but yes later
•	Where do you plan on deploying? 
o	FIS DCs
•	Are you going to run containers? 
o	Yes

attributes.description:
5/23/18 – Dave Waller (Linux Admin / Cloud Enginerr) also Dave’s Team – Tim Lucas Cloud Engineer, Tyler Seevers Manager of Team, and a network and linux admin. With Jude and Shawn from Red Hat storage team.

Gluster as storage for application servers. Setting up servers in different availability zones. They want to set shared storage underneath them but have it available for multiple app servers from multiple points and replicated. (AWS)

Active active cluster with backups. Moving to this mainly because they have two problems with Amazons EFS service – backups are pain – cant do snap – and performance. Their app will read and write data at a decent rate so they need better performance. Big things though are setting up cluster and failover. Common pain points.

Testing 3.8 or 3.12 Gluster (whatever was long term stable release). Been trying to get demo license but only got lab. Could they use native guster FS instead of NFS. They are worried it was slower, but Shawn is saying that’s not true. If solves problem they will role with it. 

Replica 3 arbiter 1 installation. Gives them 3 copies with 2X the data suggestion by Shawn. High available as they can get. Highest available option within Amazon. May want to go multi region for AWS, can they span across regions? Not yet. Technology currently in community, want it stable before we incorporate – Halo is what its called. Can do active/passive across regions. 

Jude gave MSRP pricing. ($12k Year)

Next Steps – Get them a supported eval. 60 Days. High availability installation to evaluate and Shawn would like to walk them through installation in POC (supported bits and supported configuration). 

If all prepped in advance with GDeploy Shawn would want an hour to help with Install (should not take that much time). 

May29th in the afternoon sync up with Shawn for this deploy. 2-4 Central. SC Datacenter is affiliate of Colony Brands.

attributes.description:
Opportunity Scope:
800 Networking nodes to start
2,000 total

5,000 server nodes (mostly all windows)

Randy Fleming - IT Lead Response 


We will presumably be using Ansible Tower to manage Ansible related (server) infrastructure to keep that ecosystem self-contained. Our current perception is Ansible is superior for managing network devices and Puppet is superior managing wide-scale Windows servers so we expect to be using both platforms where appropriate.

 

For our broader server infrastructure context (1500+ windows servers, lots of physical, 100 or so Linux) the current plan is to bring in Puppet to manage those nodes. Ultimately, we may end up all-in on either Ansible or Puppet depending on functionality, and perhaps most importantly, cost.

 

All of this is unproven technology for us as we have not yet used either technology at any scale up to this point and it comes with a high price tag, so all options are on the table as to where we ultimately land in the long run.

 

Appreciate your help getting our pricing together, this will help us make the business case we’re trying to build to justify the expense of a new tool. As you might expect, we have lots of tools already, so there’s always a good bit of skepticism to overcome when we propose to add “yet another tool” to the environment, particularly a very expensive one.

attributes.description:
8/1/18 Initial Discovery Call Notes (PW): 

- James is leading work in trying to migrate to Satellite 6 but is currently not a fan of the current interface that they are working with 
- He is looking to explore other solutions in the space for automation like Ansible Tower due to processing problems that his Windows and Linux systems are experiencing 
- They are currently also moving away from AIX 
- They are also having trouble with DISA STIG compliance in terms of manually have to scan their systems throughout the network 
- His specific group handles the processing of PII for enlistment records and managing the data coming into their systsems 
- James rolls up to Mark Gutman who is associated with a 300k opportunity from 2017 for the HQ out of Chicago 
- That opportunity was worked by Alec Littell and our team went onsite to meeting with their large networking group that would essentially make the enterprise purchase if it got back to that level 
- Alec mentioned that Mark Gutman is a low level contractor that was initially included in those discussions 
- That specific opportunity eventually went to an RFP and contracting on their end did not draft an accurate outline of the deal and at some point the Frank Longor who was the head of the purchase on their end stopped responding to calls and emails from our end 
- I spoke with Chip and the plan is to work with James under the radar and see if we can assist him with his Satellite and Ansible Tower interest. If we can successfully get him working with a pilot we might be able to use that success to bring up the previous discussions with the HQ networking group
